        <!-- Step 01: Publisher signs -->
        <div class="scroll-step signed-step" data-step="signed">
          <span class="step-num">01 · SIGNED</span>
          <h3>Publisher signs.</h3>
          <p>
            Add one GitHub Actions workflow. MOAT generates a signed manifest for your
            content, anchors a log entry in Sigstore Rekor, and pushes the manifest to
            your registry branch.
          </p>
          <p>
            No key material leaves your pipeline. The signing identity is your OIDC token
            from GitHub Actions — nothing to rotate, nothing to store.
          </p>
        </div>

        <!-- Step 02: Registry attests -->
        <div class="scroll-step attested-step" data-step="attested">
          <span class="step-num">02 · ATTESTED</span>
          <h3>Registry attests.</h3>
          <p>
            The registry picks up the signed manifest and adds its own attestation —
            what was indexed, when, and by whom. The full chain is queryable
            by anyone.
          </p>
          <p>
            Registries don't need to run their own infrastructure. One workflow file
            is enough.
          </p>
        </div>

        <!-- Step 03: Consumer verifies -->
        <div class="scroll-step verified-step" data-step="verified">
          <span class="step-num">03 · VERIFIED</span>
          <h3>Consumer verifies.</h3>
          <p>
            Run <code>moat-verify</code> before installing. It checks the content hash
            against the registry attestation and confirms the signature is present
            in Rekor.
          </p>
          <p>
            Tampered content fails. Content from an unknown registry fails. The install
            only proceeds on a clean chain of custody.
          </p>
        </div>

